{
  "answer": "**Charles Comte provides a precise definition of *la liberté* (liberty) in Chapter 3 (\"De ce qui constitue la liberté\") of *Traité de la propriété*, Volume I.**\n\nHe states: \"in this work, this word simply designates **the state of a person who encounters, in his fellow men, no obstacle, whether to the regular development of his being, or to the innocent exercise of his faculties**.\"[^1]\n\nComte notes that other philosophers and jurists have defined liberty differently, but this is his chosen definition for the work, which he qualifies by negations (i.e., the absence of slavery's elements, detailed throughout the chapter). He adds that any obscurity dissipates by reference to his prior discussion of human faculties' perfection.[^1] Later, he contrasts it directly with slavery's principle: \"**a man can never be legitimately possessed by another, and that the products of his labors belong only to him, so long as he has not freely alienated them**.\"[^2]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété*, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/03-de-ce-qui-constitue-la-liberte/translation/#p-1c5676).\n[^2]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété*, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/03-de-ce-qui-constitue-la-liberte/translation/#p-86c544).",
